Fig. 1. A sample micro Data Video (mDV) [
58
] from Study 1, annotated with its narrative composition based
on Cohns commonly adopted narrative categories [
14
], along with a Linker element. Despite being under a
minute long, the video contains a full narrative arc structure with an Establisher segment, two Initial units, one
Peak, and multiple Release Units. Additionally, the video ends with a Linker prompting viewers to subscribe
to the channel for more similar videos. The Linker allows the video designer to provide the audience access to
more information while keeping the video brief. It was found that the Linker is oen strategically used to
direct viewers aention to certain content whether the goal is to provide more information, collect more
views/subscriptions, or advertise for a certain product/service.

A.4 The Final Codebook
Table 4. The Final Codebook used to analyze the storyboarding process in Study 2.
1. Read and understand the data
(Data/information familiarization activities)
is is more like an exploration or preparation stage, in which participants
(i.e., video designers) go through the provided information and material to
gain an understanding on the topic or search for specic data/information
to support the narrative
2. Select data/information and corresponding
visualization from the given sheet
(Information and data selection activities)
Decisions to select or discard specic pieces of information or data facts as well as
decisions and discussions on the data visualization type to be used.
While this is closely coupled with the Read and Interpret Data activity,
activities in this category always include decisions about specic facts whether to
include or discard them and/or how to visualize them while
the aim of Read and Interpret is just to explore and gain knowledge about
the topic and the available facts.
3. Cra the Narrative
Activities related to coming up with the overall storyline via putting together and
arranging the content. is includes but not limited to
1) selecting the overall theme
2) createing a meaningful transition between scenes
3) deciding on the hook or the opening scene as well as the ending
4) discussing strategies for data fact usage or dierent elements of the video
Unpacking Micro Data Videos MHCI036:29
4. Engage Viewers
Discussions and design techniques related to engaging viewers
(not about the story content per se); such as the addition of animation, sound eects,
BG music or various visual/auditorial eects.
MHCI036:30 Sallam et al.

B.1 Information Sheet Used in the Study
CHILDRENS OUTSIDE PLAY
W H A T I S OU T D O OR P L AY ? A ND WH Y I S
I T IM P O R TA N T ?
Outdoor play is unstructured, freely chosen and child-directed
outdoor activity (e.g., climbing, racing, and independent exploration).
Outdoor play offers benefits that are not available when playing
inside as it tends to involve children feeling more freedom, being
more physically active, moving their bodies in different ways, and
playing differently than they would inside.
B E NI FI T S OF O U T S ID E P LA Y
Outside play offers opportunities for unstructured play which can:
Improve attention, concentration, and memory
Increase physical activity levels
Strengthen social and emotional learning
Support resilience and self-regulation
Improve mental health and well-being
R I SK Y P L A Y A S SO C IA T E D
W I TH OU T S I DE PL A Y
Play at heights
Play at high speed
Play with tools
Play near elements
Play with a chance of getting lost
Rough and tumble play
B A RR I ER S T O O UT S ID E P LA Y
Risk aversive cultural norms
Anxieties about childrens
educational attainment and safety
Teachers interests and competencies
School and district culture and policies
physical environment challenges

R I S KY PL A Y
By allowing children to make
their own decisions about how
they use their own bodies, we
are helping them learn to take

H O W T O H E L P C H I L DE R E N
P L A Y O UT S I D E M O R E

Extra Resources
Outsideplay.ca tool to help parents and educators gain the confidence and
skills to support childrens outdoor play.
The Unstructured play project by Canadian Public Health Association.
D A TA F A C T S
Only 37% of children play outside everyday (https://outsideplay.ca/).
Only 7% of kids under 10 are allowed to go out on their own.
According to Canadian guidelines and WHO recommendations, children
need to be active for at least 180 minutes a day.
Only 21% of children in Canada play more than 1.5 hours per day.
The likelihood of dying from an injury is 0.0059%.
The odds of total stranger abduction are 1 in 14 million (RCMP).
Canadian children are 8 times more likely to die as a passenger in a
motor vehicle than from being hit by a vehicle when outside on foot or
on a bike.(Public Health Agency of Canada).
Only 33% of children meet the recommended physical activity
guidelines (https://outsideplay.ca/).
For every hour spent outdoors, children get 7 min of moderate to vigorous
physical activity and 762 steps.
